data.name: Label88.Text
data.value: Use "Import Movies" to scan your movie directories, retrieve media info and internet data, add the movies to your catalog and optionally remove movies you don't have anymore from your catalog. Depending on your settings, this can be done with or without user interaction (e.g. user dialog if movie can't be identified automatically) or if a non identified movie should be added without internet data.

data.name: chkDontAskInteractive.ToolTip
data.value: Only effective, if you have chosen the internet lookup behaviour as "try to find best match automatically". If unchecked, you will get a dialog for each movie AMCUpdater cannot automatically match. If checked, you won't get a dialog - instead AMCupdater is importing the movie without internet data.

data.name: chkImportOnInternetFailInGuiMode.ToolTip
data.value: If you want AMCupdater to import files in AMCupdater interactive GUI mode, you can set this option. Note: To set the behaviour for usage from within MyFilms plugin in background import mode, use "Import behaviour in MyFilms".

data.name: chkImportOnInternetFail.ToolTip
data.value: Continue processing and import files even when Internet lookup fails or similar. This is the preferred setting for silent background operation, if you prefer to have your media files imported, even if the internet lookup is failing. It gives you the possibility to update the internet infos interactively in MyFilms.

data.name: cbInternetLookupBehaviour.ToolTip
data.value:
Here you can choose how AMC Updater handles the import of your files, depending on the matching. You can choose several use cases, that allow unattended, partly or fully interactive import of new files. When you select an Import Behaviour, you'll get a short description below. A good idea when importing many movies is to first run unattended with 'Auto match only' and afterwards another run using interactive mode.
Note: If you don't have e.g. the year in the directory or movie name, AMCupdater most probably will not get good matches on movie searches. To get good matches automatically, year should be in directory or filename in brackets - e.g. "movie name (1982)"

data.name: cbTitleHandling.ToolTip
data.value:
Options are: File Name: use file name for title field Folder Name: use folder name for title field Relative Name: use whole content of path for title
File Name + Internet Lookup Folder Name + Internet Lookup Relative Name + Internet Lookup
All the same as above, but adding internet lookup, trying to get a matching movie and then replacing title with the title found by the internet grabber.
Example: So if you have named your files by movie title, select “title”. If you have your movie files in folders, that have the movie title, select “folder”.

data.name: txtParserFilePath.ToolTip
data.value: Enter the location of an Internet Parser file. These files allow AMCUpdater to access Internet Movie sites to get movie information Various Parser Files are provided by default - they are in the Scripts sub-folder of the AMCUpdater application folder.

data.name: chkPurgeMissingAlways.ToolTip
data.value: When checked, all files, that are not accessible will be removed from your DB. If unchecked, only files will be removed, that are on an accessible path. Thus movies from unavailable paths (e.g. removed USB drive) won't be removed.

data.name: chkPurgeMissing.ToolTip
data.value:
Checks your Ant Movie Database catalog for references to files which no longer exist. If orphaned entries are found, they will be purged from the database. This only affects database entries which reference the currently scanned movie folder(s). Override path is taken into account for this option. For example, an entry listing a Source of 'd:\Movies' will not be considered an orphan if you only scan 'e:\Other Movies'.
Entries with sources outside the scan directories are not purged automatically - only entries with sources within the active scan folders will be purged automatically.
If you want to purge entries regardless of the path is available, you need to also enable "Purge Orphans when Source is unavailable". this will remove all entries, that are currently not available. Useful, e.g. if you had once connected a USB drive and want to get rid of those imported films. Caution: If you store your movies e.g. on a NAS and the NAS is offline, this option will remove all movies from your catalog DB !With this option enabled,

data.name: chkManualDontAskInteractive.ToolTip
data.value:
Check this, if you want to update your movie data without user interaction. If a movie can't be identified automatically, it will NOT show the user dialog for manual selection. Thus the (internet) movie data cannot be retrieved and updated.
Note: Auto matching depends very much on your database structure; if you have e.g. IMDb links stored in URL field and try updating with IMDb grabber script, auto match will always work due to usage if IMDb id. Other grabber scripts require matching by name and year, that might not always allow auto matches.

data.name: cbManualInternetLookupBehaviour.ToolTip
data.value:
Auto match only: Will only update movie with internet data, if the movie can be 'auto matched' and skip otherwise Check this, if you want to update your movie data without user interaction. If a movie can't be identified automatically, it will NOT show the user dialog for manual selection. Thus the (internet) movie data cannot be retrieved and updated.
Auto match & ask if no match: Will automatically update movie, if it can be 'auto matched' and pop a dialog for manual selection otherwise.
Manual match (always ask): Will ask for each movie for selection.
Note: If you want to update you catalog unattended, you have to choose 'Auto match only' - but you must be aware, that no data will be updated, if the matching cannot be done. Auto matching depends very much on your database structure; if you have e.g. IMDb links stored in URL field and try updating with IMDb grabber script, auto match will always work due to usage if IMDb id. Other grabber scripts require matching by name and year, that might not always allow auto matches.

data.name: chkLoadPersonImagesWithFanart.ToolTip
data.value: AMC Updater can also load person images, when retrieving fanart for a movie to display person thumbs in GUI. As prerequisites a person artwork folder has to be defined. However, the loading time increases substantially - uncheck this option, if you need faster grabbing of fanart.

data.name: chkUseGrabberForFanart.ToolTip
data.value: By default, AMCU uses the internal fanart grabber for grabbing fanart from TMDb. When checked, the script definitions are used to load fanart instead. This allows to get fanart from other sources, e.g. from other websites (if the script supports it) or from movie directory, when using nfo grabber script. Two definitions are used: For single fanart, use the fanart definition at cover image; for multiple fanart, use the definition of "MultiFanart" in the script.

data.name: cbEditionNameAppliesTo.ToolTip
data.value: You can add "Edition Name(s)" to the end of the title. AMCUpdater tries to get those Edition Names (like "Directors Cut, Unrated, Extended Edition) from the media name. You can add it to Original Title, Translated Title or Both.

data.name: txtSeriesNameIdentifier.ToolTip
data.value:
You can define a search expression to identify the folder to be used for "series name". Other than "group name" this will add the complete path hierarchy from the detected field - so when browsing in MyFilms plugin you'll get a "series hierarchy" presented.
If left empty, the standard rules apply. If a search expression is defined, AMCUpdater will check your file path and only directory names containing the search expression will be added as group/series name - independent of their relative position. The match closest to the media file is used (if multiple directories match the search expression).
Example: Search expression = "(Series)" Series\24 (Series)\Season 1\24-s01e01.avi Series\24 (Series)\Season 1\24-s01e02.avi Series\24 (Series)\Season 2\24-s02e01.avi

data.name: txtGroupNameIdentifier.ToolTip
data.value:
You can define a search expression to identify the folder to be used for "group name". If left empty, the standard rules apply. If a search expression is defined, AMCUpdater will check your file path and only directory names containing the search expression will be added as group/series name - independent of their relative position. The match closest to the media file is used (if multiple directories match the search expression).
Example: Search expression = "Collection" Movies\Matrix\media file.avi Movies\Star Trek Collection\Star Trek 1\media file.avi Movies\Star Trek Collection\Star Trek 2\media file.avi Collections\Star Trek Collection\Star Trek 9\movie.avi 2, 3 and 4 will return "Star Trek" as group name

data.name: chkFolderNameIsGroupName.ToolTip
data.value:
The MyFilms plugin supports the use of a Group Identifier to group movies together. Normally used for film Trilogies and so on. The update will attempt to work out which films are grouped based on the folder structure. The movie title will then be saved as 'Group name \ Movie Name'.
Note: The group name is depending on the setting of "Title and Search Handling": - "File" -> the folder containing the file will be returned as group name. - "Folder" -> the parent folder of the movie folder will be returned as group name.

data.name: chkReadDVDLabel.ToolTip
data.value:
When importing movies from CD or DVD: Will attempt to read the disk label and use that in the Media Label field. When importing movies from local disk: Will attempt to read volume name. When importing movies from network storage: Will attempt to read UNC server name.
If not found then the value entered for 'Media Label' will be used (if any).

data.name: txtPictureFilenameSuffix.ToolTip
data.value: Allows to add an ending to the picture filename. This is e.g. useful, if you import several editions of the same movie to make sure to not overwrite existing images - in that case you could add the year as suffix. Supported placeholder: %year% %number% If using placeholders, the suffix will only be added, if placeholder value is not empty.

data.name: cbPictureHandling.ToolTip
data.value:
The location of your cover art files is stored in the Ant Movie Catalog 'Picture' field. You can refer to the file as a relative ('\covers\moviename.jpg') or full ('c:\covers\moviename.jpg') path. You can also store the cover art as 'folder.jpg' - this is only suitable if you store your movies in separate folders (one movie per folder) If using Folder.jpg - the system will use any existing file on import and will create one (if available online) if not.
"Create Movie thumb" is an option to create and use thumbnails created from the movie content (thumbnailer). Usage: Disable internet lookup, enable Picture/Fanart and choose "Cover Thumbnail" in Picture Handling. This is especially useful, if you have private movies, documentaries etc. where usually is no artwork available.

data.name: txtPictureFilenamePrefix.ToolTip
data.value: Alter this field to change the location and name of downloaded cover art. By default the images are stored in the same folder as your Ant database file. If you enter a relative folder path, this will be used as a sub-folder i.e. 'covers\' will create / use a sub-folder called 'covers'. You can also add a prefix to the cover art filenames - this is for compatibility with Ant Movie Catalog which also does this. i.e. 'covers\MyDB' will save the images in the 'covers' sub-folder, and the images will be named 'MyDBmoviename.jpg'.

data.name: GroupBox28.ToolTip
data.value: You can define search expressions with replacement expressions to identify "Edition" from (media) name. Both normal and Regex search expressions are allowed. If the expression is found, the replacement expression will be returned. If multiple rules apply, the Replacement expression will be returned as comma separated list. You can enable on Database Tab to add Edition to end of title. By that you can differentiate different editions of a movie.

data.name: txtOverridePath.ToolTip
data.value: Override path when writing to XML file: Use this field to change the path to your files. Normally used if you are scanning local files (i.e. d:\Movies) but your MediaPortal client will access them over the network (i.e. \\server\Movies\) The over-ride path will replace the 'Path to Movies Folder'. Note : Can only be used when scanning a single folder structure.

data.name: Label46.Text
data.value: These options allow you to filter which files and folders are scanned and how to treat the filenames discovered. You can filter out files or folders based on their names, as well as stripping out any unwanted characters / text strings. The file and folder exclusion lists are case-insensitive string comparisons; the 'strip characters from title' list supports Regex expressions.

data.name: GroupBox26.ToolTip
data.value: You can set several options for the internet grabber. Be aware, that not all options are supported by all grabber scripts. However, IMDb (full) script should support all options listed here. If you set no values, the default settings of the grabber will be used instead. The default settings (of the grabber script) can be changed by editing the grabber script in the "MyFilms Grabber Interface" ("Edit script").

data.name: chkGrabberOverrideLanguage.ToolTip
data.value:
Preferred Language(s) for Translated Title(s) and Certification
Depending on the abilities of your grabber script, you can set a language/country here to tell the grabber to get related infos. Most internet sites only support titles for different countries - IMDb-Full script also supports Certification for different countries. Note: To use Certification, you have to map that data to one of the standard fields of your ANT Movie Catalog. Note: You can add more than one language/country using comma separated values. Example: You would like to grab titles for Germany and Canada you set "Germany, Canada". As the dropdown only allows choosing one value, multiple values have to be entered manually.

data.name: btnExcludeFileDelete.ToolTip
data.value: "reset" will delete the exclusions file - so all movies you might have added in the past will be handled by importer again. When you add new exclusions, the file will automatically be recreated. AMC Updater takes a backup for you, in case you accidentally have reset and want to restore manually.

data.name: txtExcludeFilePath.ToolTip
data.value: AMCUpdater can be instructed to ignore selected files. These files will never be scanned or imported by AMCUpdater. If the file does not exist; it will be created the first time you select 'Ignore' on a movie. Note: It is sufficient, to set path and name to a file - AMCUpdater will auto-create it on first use.

data.name: chkParseSubtitleFiles.ToolTip
data.value: When enabled, AMCUpdater will look for and analyse .IDX subtitle index files. These files will be scanned to determine what languages are included, if possible. This does not affect the detection of external subtitle files - but may improve the results if you use .IDX files.

data.name: txtTrailerIentificationStrings.ToolTip
data.value: If a file contains one of these strings, it will be identified as trailer instead of movie several values are possible - use ";" as delimiter. You can also use Regex Expressions, but they must NOT contain the ';' charcter, as this is used to separate the expressions.
